1. Introduction

1.1 Purpose and Scope

This document provides a comprehensive technical architecture and implementation guide for the QUENNE Energy System (QES). It is intended for system architects, hardware engineers, embedded software developers, and grid operators who will design, build, deploy, and maintain the system. The scope covers the entire stack—from physical energy harvesting hardware to cloud-based grid orchestration AI—with detailed specifications, component choices, algorithms, and integration steps.

1.2 System Overview

The QES is a distributed energy generation network that captures kinetic energy from moving vehicles using two types of harvesters:

· Roadway Infrastructure Harvesters embedded in roads, speed bumps, or rumble strips.
· Vehicle Integrated Generators built into vehicle suspensions (regenerative shock absorbers).

Each harvester is an intelligent node running local control algorithms (Atomic Fusion, Booster Fusion) on a secure real-time embedded platform (Linux Core). Thousands of these nodes communicate with a central Nuclear Intelligence grid orchestrator that optimizes energy flow, maintains grid stability, and performs predictive maintenance. The system adheres to ethical and safety guidelines enforced by the TRIAD governance layer.

---

2. Architectural Foundation: QUENNE Stacked Intelligence

The QES is built upon the eight-layer QUENNE Stacked Intelligence model. Each layer has specific responsibilities and interfaces with adjacent layers.

2.1 Layer 8: Human Authority & TRIAD Governance

· Purpose: Define immutable operational principles: ethics, strategy, safety.
· Implementation:
  · Ethical (Michael): Enforces material compliance (e.g., conflict-free minerals) and lifecycle sustainability (recyclability >90%). Rules are encoded as high-level constraints passed to Layer 7.
  · Strategic (Gabriel): Sets global optimization objectives: minimize carbon footprint, ensure equitable energy distribution, maximize grid resilience. These are translated into weightings in the MPC cost function.
  · Protective (Rafael): Mandates safety standards (IEEE 1547 anti-islanding) and cybersecurity policies (NIST IR 8473). These are enforced via configuration and monitoring at Layer 2 and Layer 7.

2.2 Layer 7: Nuclear Intelligence (Grid Orchestration)

· Purpose: City-wide optimization of energy harvesting, storage, and distribution.
· Implementation: A central software service running Model Predictive Control (MPC) on aggregated data from all nodes. It produces setpoints (e.g., power draw, standby mode) sent down to Layer 6.

2.3 Layer 6: Atomic Fusion Algorithm (Local Control)

· Purpose: Real-time control of an individual harvester node using sensor fusion and impedance matching.
· Implementation: Runs on the node’s microcontroller; takes local sensor data (vibration, displacement, temperature, voltage/current) and adjusts the electrical load via PWM to maximize power transfer. Communicates with Layer 5 for adaptive tuning.

2.4 Layer 5: Booster Fusion Algorithm (Adaptive Scaling / MPPT)

· Purpose: Dynamically tune the harvester’s operating point to track maximum power (mechanical MPPT).
· Implementation: An extremum-seeking or perturb-and-observe algorithm that varies the load and observes power output, finding the optimal point. This layer also adjusts parameters based on long-term changes (e.g., seasonal road conditions).

2.5 Layer 4: Hybrid Photonic-Electronic Sensing & Quantum Computation

· Purpose: Advanced sensing for predictive maintenance and future quantum optimization.
· Implementation:
  · Photonic Sensors: Fiber Bragg gratings embedded in critical components (bearings, springs) to measure strain and temperature. Data is processed locally (Layer 6) and sent to Layer 7 for trend analysis.
  · Quantum Optimization (future): For ultra-large-scale deployments (>1M nodes), quantum annealing (e.g., D-Wave) could solve grid balancing problems. Currently a research placeholder.

2.6 Layer 3: Engineering Algorithm & Physical Harvester

· Purpose: The physical embodiment of the harvester; parametric design optimized via genetic algorithms.
· Implementation: Detailed hardware designs (see Section 3).

2.7 Layer 2: Linux Core & Real-Time Operating System

· Purpose: Secure, reliable digital backbone for each node.
· Implementation: Embedded System-on-Module (e.g., Toradex Verdin i.MX8M Mini) running a real-time Linux kernel (PREEMPT_RT) with Yocto Project build. Manages local algorithms, secure boot, encrypted storage, and communication.

2.8 Layer 1: Cross-Platform Abstraction & Communication

· Purpose: Ensure interoperability across diverse hardware and networks.
· Implementation: All nodes implement IEEE 2030.5 (Smart Energy Profile 2.0) data models and communicate via MQTT over TLS. REST APIs are provided for management.

---

3. Hardware Implementation

3.1 Roadway Infrastructure Harvester

3.1.1 Mechanical Design

· Type: Crank-slider mechanism converting vertical displacement to rotary motion.
· Displacement: Max 25 mm (to avoid driver discomfort).
· Return Spring: High-cycle fatigue steel (9260) rated for 10^7 cycles.
· Enclosure: IP68-rated stainless steel housing with drainage.

3.1.2 Electromagnetic Generator

· Type: Permanent Magnet Synchronous Generator (PMSG), radial flux.
· Rotor: Surface-mounted NdFeB N42SH magnets, 8-pole configuration.
· Stator: 12-slot, 3-phase concentrated winding, Litz wire to reduce eddy losses.
· Rated Speed: 300 RPM (peak from vehicle pass).
· Peak Power: ~5 W per vehicle pass at 30 mph.

3.1.3 Power Electronics & Energy Buffering

· Rectifier: Three-phase active rectifier (MOSFET-based) with synchronous rectification for efficiency.
· MPPT Controller: Implemented in firmware (Booster Fusion).
· Energy Buffer: 100F supercapacitor bank (Maxwell DuraBlue) to smooth pulses.
· Grid Interface: Bidirectional DC-DC converter (buck-boost) for feeding into 48V DC microgrid or AC inverter for grid-tie.

3.1.4 Embedded Controller Hardware

· SoM: Toradex Verdin i.MX8M Mini (ARM Cortex-A53, 1.5 GHz) with 1 GB RAM.
· Peripherals:
  · ADS131M04 24-bit delta-sigma ADC for current/voltage sensing.
  · MEMS accelerometer (ADXL357) for vibration measurement.
  · Temperature sensors (PT100) on bearings.
  · CAN interface for local communication.
  · Ethernet or cellular modem (for remote sites).

3.2 Vehicle Integrated Generator (Regenerative Suspension)

3.2.1 Linear Generator Topology

· Type: Tubular Permanent Magnet Linear Generator (TPMLG) integrated into shock absorber.
· Stroke: ±50 mm typical.
· Outer Diameter: 80 mm (compatible with standard shock mounting).

3.2.2 Magnetic Array Design

· Configuration: Quasi-Halbach array to maximize flux linkage.
· Magnets: NdFeB N52, axially magnetized rings.
· Spacers: High-permeability electrical steel between magnets to focus flux.
· Pole Pitch: 12 mm.
· Number of Poles: 16 (for 16-pole/16-slot design) giving peak power ~580 W .

3.2.3 Stator and Coil Configuration

· Stator Core: Segmented laminated electrical steel (0.2 mm M250-35A) to minimize eddy losses.
· Coils: Concentrated windings, 16 slots, 3-phase. Each coil: 50 turns of AWG 18 magnet wire.
· Phase Resistance: ~0.5 Ω.
· Cooling: Passive via shock absorber fluid and housing.

3.2.4 Power Conditioning for EV Integration

· Rectifier: Three-phase active rectifier (e.g., Infineon FS820R08A6P2) with MPPT control.
· DC-DC Converter: Bidirectional buck-boost (e.g., Vicor BCM) to match EV traction battery voltage (400V or 800V).
· Energy Storage: Optionally a small supercapacitor for transient buffering.

3.2.5 Controller and Vehicle Interface

· Microcontroller: Infineon AURIX TC377 (automotive grade, ASIL-D) for safety-critical functions.
· Communication: CAN FD to vehicle ECU, reporting harvested power and diagnostics.
· Power Supply: Powered from 12V vehicle auxiliary battery.

---

4. Firmware Architecture

4.1 Real-Time Operating System and Framework

· OS: PREEMPT_RT Linux on i.MX8M Mini (roadway) / AURIX uses AUTOSAR (vehicle).
· Framework: ROS 2 (Robot Operating System) for modular node-based development (roadway).

4.2 Atomic Fusion Algorithm Implementation

· Purpose: Sensor fusion and real-time control.
· Inputs:
  · Accelerometer data (FFT to extract dominant frequency).
  · Displacement (from encoder or Hall sensors).
  · Phase currents and voltages (from ADC).
· Processing: Kalman filter to estimate state (position, velocity).
· Output: PWM duty cycle for active rectifier switches to control load impedance.
· Update Rate: 10 kHz.

4.3 Booster Fusion MPPT Algorithm

· Algorithm: Perturb & Observe (P&O) adapted for mechanical input.
· Steps:
  1. Measure current power output.
  2. Perturb load (change PWM duty cycle by small step).
  3. Measure new power.
  4. If power increased, continue in same direction; else reverse.
· Adaptation: Step size is adjusted based on rate of change of input frequency (to avoid oscillation).
· Implementation: Runs as a separate ROS 2 node with lower priority (100 Hz).

4.4 Sensor Fusion and Data Acquisition

· Drivers: Custom C++ drivers for ADCs, accelerometers, etc., wrapped as ROS 2 nodes.
· Time Synchronization: PTP (Precision Time Protocol) over Ethernet for roadway nodes; GPS time for vehicle nodes.

4.5 Communication Stack

· MQTT: Eclipse Mosquitto client for telemetry (power, status, faults) to Nuclear Intelligence. Topics: /city/zone/harvester_id/telemetry.
· IEEE 2030.5: Data model encoded in CBOR over MQTT.
· Configuration/Control: REST API over HTTPS for remote management (e.g., update setpoints, firmware).

4.6 Security and Secure Boot

· Secure Boot: Verified boot chain from ROM to kernel using U-Boot with signed images.
· Encrypted Storage: LUKS for sensitive data (keys, certificates).
· TLS 1.3: All communications encrypted; client certificates for node authentication.

---

5. Software Architecture: Nuclear Intelligence (Grid Orchestrator)

5.1 Overview and Responsibilities

Nuclear Intelligence is a cloud-native (or on-prem) service that aggregates data from thousands of harvesters and optimizes grid operations. It provides:

· Real-time monitoring and control.
· Short-term forecasting (energy yield, demand).
· Model Predictive Control for optimal dispatch.
· Predictive maintenance alerts.

5.2 Data Ingestion and Time-Series Database

· Ingestion: MQTT broker cluster (EMQX) with Kafka for stream processing.
· Database: InfluxDB (time-series) for telemetry; PostgreSQL for asset metadata.
· Stream Processing: Apache Flink for real-time aggregation (e.g., 5-minute averages per zone).

5.3 Model Predictive Control (MPC) Engine

· Model: State-space model of the grid dynamics, including harvesters, storage, and loads.
· Optimization: Solved using OSQP (Operator Splitting Quadratic Program) or custom interior-point solver.
· Horizon: 15 minutes with 1-minute steps.
· Objective: Minimize weighted sum of:
  · Cost of energy from external grid.
  · Carbon emissions.
  · Inequality (deviation from equitable distribution).
· Constraints: Voltage limits, line capacities, harvester ramp rates.
· Output: Setpoints (e.g., power draw from each zone) sent to harvesters via MQTT.

5.4 Fault Detection and Predictive Maintenance

· Data: Vibration spectra, temperature trends, power output efficiency.
· Model: Autoencoder neural network trained on normal data; reconstruction error indicates anomalies.
· Alerting: When anomaly score exceeds threshold, create maintenance ticket and notify operators.

5.5 User Interfaces and APIs

· Dashboard: Grafana dashboards for real-time monitoring.
· REST API: For external systems (e.g., utility SCADA) to query status and historical data.
· Admin UI: React-based for manual override and configuration.

---

6. Communication Protocols and Data Models

6.1 IEEE 2030.5 (Smart Energy Profile 2.0)

· Profile: Defines common data structures for DERs (Distributed Energy Resources).
· Mapping: Each harvester is a Device with PowerStatus, Reading, DERControl objects.
· Encoding: CBOR (Concise Binary Object Representation) for efficiency.

6.2 MQTT for Real-Time Telemetry

· Topics:
  · qes/{node_id}/telemetry – periodic status (power, voltage, temperature).
  · qes/{node_id}/event – alarms, state changes.
  · qes/{node_id}/command – setpoints from orchestrator (via retained messages).
· QoS: QoS 1 for telemetry, QoS 2 for commands.

6.3 REST API for Management

· Endpoints:
  · GET /nodes – list all harvesters.
  · GET /nodes/{id} – details.
  · POST /nodes/{id}/config – update configuration.
  · POST /firmware – initiate OTA update.

6.4 Security: TLS, Certificates, and Authentication

· PKI: Private CA issues certificates to each node during manufacturing.
· TLS 1.3: Mandatory for all MQTT and HTTPS connections.
· Authentication: Client certificates (mutual TLS) for node-to-broker.

---

7. Deployment and Scaling

7.1 Pilot Deployment (Phase 1)

· Location: 1 km test track or controlled city street.
· Nodes: 50 roadway harvesters + 10 instrumented vehicles.
· Duration: 6 months.
· Goals: Validate hardware durability, fine-tune algorithms, measure real-world energy yield.

7.2 City-Scale Rollout (Phase 2)

· Deployment: 500 nodes in a district, integrated with existing streetlights and traffic signals.
· Infrastructure: Install microgrid (48V DC) to aggregate power before feeding to AC grid.
· Data Integration: Connect Nuclear Intelligence to utility SCADA for demand response.

7.3 Integration with Existing Grid Infrastructure

· Interconnection: Comply with IEEE 1547; use certified inverters for AC grid-tie.
· Communication: Use utility-approved protocols (DNP3) for SCADA integration.

7.4 Fleet Vehicle Integration

· Partnerships: Work with EV manufacturers or fleet operators (buses, delivery vans) to install regenerative shocks.
· Data Aggregation: Vehicles report harvested energy via cellular network; treated as mobile nodes in Nuclear Intelligence.

---

8. Testing and Validation

8.1 Hardware Testing (Lab and Field)

· Mechanical Fatigue: Test springs and bearings to 10^7 cycles.
· Environmental: IP68, temperature cycling (-40°C to +85°C), salt spray.
· EMC: Compliance with FCC/CE for radiated emissions.

8.2 Firmware Validation

· Unit Tests: Google Test for algorithm modules.
· HIL (Hardware-in-the-Loop): Simulate road profiles with dynamometer; verify MPPT tracking.

8.3 Software Simulation and HIL

· City-Scale Simulator: Custom Python tool (in repo) to model energy yield under traffic patterns.
· Co-Simulation: Integrate with grid simulator (e.g., GridLAB-D) to test MPC.

8.4 Cybersecurity Penetration Testing

· Third-party audit: Annual penetration test of all external interfaces.
· Bug Bounty Program: Encourage responsible disclosure.

---

9. Performance Metrics and Monitoring

9.1 Key Performance Indicators (KPIs)

· Energy Yield (kWh/day per node) – compare to simulation.
· MPPT Efficiency (%) – actual power / theoretical maximum.
· Node Uptime (%) – availability.
· Grid Stability Contribution – reduction in frequency deviations.
· Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF) – for mechanical components.

9.2 Dashboards and Alerts

· Real-time Dashboard: Grafana showing live power, grid frequency, alerts.
· Weekly Reports: Automated summaries for operators.
· Mobile Alerts: Push notifications for critical faults.

---

10. Conclusion

The QUENNE Energy System provides a practical, scalable, and intelligent solution for harvesting urban kinetic energy. By adhering to the layered QUENNE architecture, the system ensures ethical operation, robust security, and optimal performance. This technical architecture and implementation guide equips engineering teams with the necessary details to build, deploy, and operate QES in real-world environments.

